name: NOP
description: Does nothing.

name: SWAP
description: Same as `s1 XCHG0`.

name: XCHG_0I
description: Interchanges `s0` with `s[i]`, `1 <= i <= 15`.

name: XCHG_IJ
description: Interchanges `s[i]` with `s[j]`, `1 <= i < j <= 15`.

name: XCHG_0I_LONG
description: Interchanges `s0` with `s[ii]`, `0 <= ii <= 255`.

name: XCHG_1I
description: Interchanges `s1` with `s[i]`, `2 <= i <= 15`.

name: PUSH
description: Pushes a copy of the old `s[i]` into the stack.

name: DUP
description: Same as `s0 PUSH`.

name: OVER
description: Same as `s1 PUSH`.

name: POP
description: Pops the old `s0` value into the old `s[i]`.

name: DROP
description: Same as `s0 POP`, discards the top-of-stack value.

name: NIP
description: Same as `s1 POP`.

name: XCHG3
description: Equivalent to `s2 s[i] XCHG` `s1 s[j] XCHG` `s[k] XCHG0`.

name: XCHG2
description: Equivalent to `s1 s[i] XCHG` `s[j] XCHG0`.

name: XCPU
description: Equivalent to `s[i] XCHG0` `s[j] PUSH`.

name: PUXC
description: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `SWAP` `s[j] XCHG0`.

name: PUSH2
description: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s[j+1] PUSH`.

name: XCHG3_ALT
description: Long form of `XCHG3`.

name: XC2PU
description: Equivalent to `s[i] s[j] XCHG2` `s[k] PUSH`.

name: XCPUXC
description: Equivalent to `s1 s[i] XCHG` `s[j] s[k-1] PUXC`.

name: XCPU2
description: Equivalent to `s[i] XCHG0` `s[j] s[k] PUSH2`.

name: PUXC2
description: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s2 XCHG0` `s[j] s[k] XCHG2`.

name: PUXCPU
description: Equivalent to `s[i] s[j-1] PUXC` `s[k] PUSH`.

name: PU2XC
description: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `SWAP` `s[j] s[k-1] PUXC`.

name: PUSH3
description: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s[j+1] s[k+1] PUSH2`.

name: BLKSWAP
description:
Permutes two blocks `s[j+i+1] … s[j+1]` and `s[j] … s0`.
`0 <= i,j <= 15`
Equivalent to `[i+1] [j+1] REVERSE` `[j+1] 0 REVERSE` `[i+j+2] 0 REVERSE`.

name: ROT2
stacks: a b c d e f - c d e f a b
description: Rotates the three topmost pairs of stack entries.
stack_input: a b c d e f
stack_output: c d e f a b

name: ROLL
description:
Rotates the top `i+1` stack entries.
Equivalent to `1 [i+1] BLKSWAP`.

name: ROLLREV
description:
Rotates the top `i+1` stack entries in the other direction.
Equivalent to `[i+1] 1 BLKSWAP`.

name: PUSH_LONG
description:
Pushes a copy of the old `s[ii]` into the stack.
`0 <= ii <= 255`

name: POP_LONG
description:
Pops the old `s0` value into the old `s[ii]`.
`0 <= ii <= 255`

name: ROT
stacks: a b c - b c a
description: Equivalent to `1 2 BLKSWAP` or to `s2 s1 XCHG2`.

name: ROTREV
stacks: a b c - c a b
description: Equivalent to `2 1 BLKSWAP` or to `s2 s2 XCHG2`.

name: SWAP2
stacks: a b c d - c d a b
description: Equivalent to `2 2 BLKSWAP` or to `s3 s2 XCHG2`.

name: DROP2
description: Equivalent to `DROP` `DROP`.

name: DUP2
stacks: a b - a b a b
description: Equivalent to `s1 s0 PUSH2`.

name: OVER2
stacks: a b c d - a b c d a b
description: Equivalent to `s3 s2 PUSH2`.
stack_output: a b c d a b

name: REVERSE
description: Reverses the order of `s[j+i+1] … s[j]`.

name: BLKDROP
description: Equivalent to `DROP` performed `i` times.

name: BLKPUSH
description:
Equivalent to `PUSH s(j)` performed `i` times.
`1 <= i <= 15`, `0 <= j <= 15`.

name: PICK
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `s[i] PUSH`.

name: ROLLX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `1 [i] BLKSWAP`.

name: -ROLLX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `[i] 1 BLKSWAP`.

name: BLKSWX
description: Pops integers `i`,`j` from the stack, then performs `[i] [j] BLKSWAP`.

name: REVX
description: Pops integers `i`,`j` from the stack, then performs `[i] [j] REVERSE`.

name: DROPX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `[i] BLKDROP`.

name: TUCK
description: Equivalent to `SWAP` `OVER` or to `s1 s1 XCPU`.

name: XCHGX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `s[i] XCHG`.

name: DEPTH
description: Pushes the current depth of the stack.

name: CHKDEPTH
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then checks whether there are at least `i` elements, generating a stack underflow exception otherwise.

name: ONLYTOPX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then removes all but the top `i` elements.

name: ONLYX
description: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then leaves only the bottom `i` elements. Approximately equivalent to `DEPTH` `SWAP` `SUB` `DROPX`.

name: BLKDROP2
description:
Drops `i` stack elements under the top `j` elements.
`1 <= i <= 15`, `0 <= j <= 15`
Equivalent to `[i+j] 0 REVERSE` `[i] BLKDROP` `[j] 0 REVERSE`.

name: NULL
description: Pushes the only value of type _Null_.

name: ISNULL
description: Checks whether `x` is a _Null_, and returns `-1` or `0` accordingly.

name: TUPLE
description:
Creates a new _Tuple_ `t=(x_1, … ,x_n)` containing `n` values `x_1`,..., `x_n`.
`0 <= n <= 15`

name: NIL
description: Pushes the only _Tuple_ `t=()` of length zero.

name: SINGLE
description: Creates a singleton `t:=(x)`, i.e., a _Tuple_ of length one.

name: PAIR
description: Creates pair `t:=(x,y)`.

name: TRIPLE
description: Creates triple `t:=(x,y,z)`.

name: INDEX
description:
Returns the `k`-th element of a _Tuple_ `t`.
`0 <= k <= 15`.

name: FIRST
description: Returns the first element of a _Tuple_.

name: SECOND
description: Returns the second element of a _Tuple_.

name: THIRD
description: Returns the third element of a _Tuple_.

name: UNTUPLE
description:
Unpacks a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)` of length equal to `0 <= n <= 15`.
If `t` is not a _Tuple_, or if `|t| != n`, a type check exception is thrown.

name: UNSINGLE
description: Unpacks a singleton `t=(x)`.

name: UNPAIR
description: Unpacks a pair `t=(x,y)`.

name: UNTRIPLE
description: Unpacks a triple `t=(x,y,z)`.

name: UNPACKFIRST
description:
Unpacks first `0 <= k <= 15` elements of a _Tuple_ `t`.
If `|t|<k`, throws a type check exception.

name: CHKTUPLE
description: Checks whether `t` is a _Tuple_. If not, throws a type check exception.

name: EXPLODE
description: Unpacks a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_m)` and returns its length `m`, but only if `m <= n <= 15`. Otherwise throws a type check exception.

name: SETINDEX
description:
Computes _Tuple_ `t'` that differs from `t` only at position `t'_{k+1}`, which is set to `x`.
`0 <= k <= 15`
If `k >= |t|`, throws a range check exception.

name: SETFIRST
description: Sets the first component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETSECOND
description: Sets the second component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETTHIRD
description: Sets the third component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: INDEXQ
description: Returns the `k`-th element of a _Tuple_ `t`, where `0 <= k <= 15`. In other words, returns `x_{k+1}` if `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`. If `k>=n`, or if `t` is _Null_, returns a _Null_ instead of `x`.

name: FIRSTQ
description: Returns the first element of a _Tuple_.

name: SECONDQ
description: Returns the second element of a _Tuple_.

name: THIRDQ
description: Returns the third element of a _Tuple_.

name: SETINDEXQ
description:
Sets the `k`-th component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x`, where `0 <= k < 16`, and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.
If `|t| <= k`, first extends the original _Tuple_ to length `n’=k+1` by setting all new components to _Null_. If the original value of `t` is _Null_, treats it as an empty _Tuple_. If `t` is not _Null_ or _Tuple_, throws an exception. If `x` is _Null_ and either `|t| <= k` or `t` is _Null_, then always returns `t'=t` (and does not consume tuple creation gas).

name: SETFIRSTQ
description: Sets the first component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETSECONDQ
description: Sets the second component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETTHIRDQ
description: Sets the third component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: TUPLEVAR
description: Creates a new _Tuple_ `t` of length `n` similarly to `TUPLE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: INDEXVAR
description: Similar to `k INDEX`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: UNTUPLEVAR
description: Similar to `n UNTUPLE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: UNPACKFIRSTVAR
description: Similar to `n UNPACKFIRST`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: EXPLODEVAR
description: Similar to `n EXPLODE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: SETINDEXVAR
description: Similar to `k SETINDEX`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: INDEXVARQ
description: Similar to `n INDEXQ`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: SETINDEXVARQ
description: Similar to `k SETINDEXQ`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: TLEN
description: Returns the length of a _Tuple_.

name: QTLEN
description: Similar to `TLEN`, but returns `-1` if `t` is not a _Tuple_.

name: ISTUPLE
description: Returns `-1` or `0` depending on whether `t` is a _Tuple_.

name: LAST
description: Returns the last element of a non-empty _Tuple_ `t`.

name: TPUSH
description: Appends a value `x` to a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`, but only if the resulting _Tuple_ `t'=(x_1,...,x_n,x)` is of length at most 255. Otherwise throws a type check exception.

name: TPOP
description: Detaches the last element `x=x_n` from a non-empty _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`, and returns both the resulting _Tuple_ `t'=(x_1,...,x_{n-1})` and the original last element `x`.

name: NULLSWAPIF
description: Pushes a _Null_ under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x!=0`.

name: NULLSWAPIFNOT
description: Pushes a _Null_ under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x=0`. May be used for stack alignment after quiet primitives such as `PLDUXQ`.

stack_output: x y or null x y

name: NULLROTRIFNOT
stacks: x y - x y or null x y
description: Pushes a _Null_ under the second stack entry from the top, but only if the topmost _Integer_ `y` is zero. May be used for stack alignment after quiet primitives such as `LDUXQ`.
stack_output: x y or null x y

name: NULLSWAPIF2
stacks: x - x or null null x

Pushes two nulls under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x!=0`.
Equivalent to `NULLSWAPIF` `NULLSWAPIF`.

stacks: x - x or null null x
description:
Pushes two nulls under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x=0`.
Equivalent to `NULLSWAPIFNOT` `NULLSWAPIFNOT`.

description:
Recovers `x=(t_{i+1})_{j+1}` for `0 <= i,j <= 3`.
Equivalent to `[i] INDEX` `[j] INDEX`.

name: CDDR

Recovers `x=t_{i+1}_{j+1}_{k+1}`.

Equivalent to `[i] [j] INDEX2` `[k] INDEX`.

name: CADDR
description: Recovers `x=t_2_2_1`.

name: CDDDR
description: Recovers `x=t_2_2_2`.

name: PUSHINT_4
description:
Pushes integer `x` into the stack. `-5 <= x <= 10`.
Here `i` equals four lower-order bits of `x` (`i=x mod 16`).

name: PUSHINT_8
description: Pushes integer `xx`. `-128 <= xx <= 127`.

name: PUSHINT_16
description: Pushes integer `xxxx`. `-2^15 <= xx < 2^15`.

name: PUSHINT_LONG
description:
Pushes integer `xxx`.
_Details:_ 5-bit `0 <= l <= 30` determines the length `n=8l+19` of signed big-endian integer `xxx`.
The total length of this instruction is `l+4` bytes or `n+13=8l+32` bits.

name: PUSHPOW2
description:
(Quietly) pushes `2^(xx+1)` for `0 <= xx <= 255`.
`2^256` is a `NaN`.

name: PUSHNAN
description: Pushes a `NaN`.

name: PUSHREF
description:
Pushes the reference `ref` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the first reference of `cc.code` into the stack as a _Cell_ (and removes this reference from the current continuation).

name: PUSHREFSLICE
description: Similar to `PUSHREF`, but converts the cell into a _Slice_.

name: PUSHREFCONT
description: Similar to `PUSHREFSLICE`, but makes a simple ordinary _Continuation_ out of the cell.

name: PUSHSLICE
description:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the (prefix) subslice of `cc.code` consisting of its first `8x+4` bits and no references (i.e., essentially a bitstring), where `0 <= x <= 15`.
A completion tag is assumed, meaning that all trailing zeroes and the last binary one (if present) are removed from this bitstring.
If the original bitstring consists only of zeroes, an empty slice will be pushed.

name: PUSHSLICE_REFS
description:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the (prefix) subslice of `cc.code` consisting of its first `1 <= r+1 <= 4` references and up to first `8xx+1` bits of data, with `0 <= xx <= 31`.
A completion tag is also assumed.

name: PUSHSLICE_LONG
description:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the subslice of `cc.code` consisting of `0 <= r <= 4` references and up to `8xx+6` bits of data, with `0 <= xx <= 127`.
A completion tag is assumed.

name: SUBR
description: Equivalent to `SWAP` `SUB`.

name: NEGATE
description:
Equivalent to `-1 MULCONST` or to `ZERO SUBR`.
Notice that it triggers an integer overflow exception if `x=-2^256`.

name: INC
description: Equivalent to `1 ADDCONST`.

name: DEC
description: Equivalent to `-1 ADDCONST`.

name: DIV_BASE
tlb: #A9 m:uint1 s:uint2 cdft:(Either [ d:uint2 f:uint2 ] [ d:uint2 f:uint2 tt:uint8 ])
description:
This is the general encoding of division, with an optional pre-multiplication and an optional replacement of the division or multiplication by a shift. Variable fields are as follows:
`0 <= m <= 1`  -  Indicates whether there is pre-multiplication (`MULDIV` and its variants), possibly replaced by a left shift.
`0 <= s <= 2`  -  Indicates whether either the multiplication or the division have been replaced by shifts: `s=0` - no replacement, `s=1` - division replaced by a right shift, `s=2` - multiplication replaced by a left shift (possible only for `m=1`).
`0 <= c <= 1`  -  Indicates whether there is a constant one-byte argument `tt` for the shift operator (if `s!=0`). For `s=0`, `c=0`. If `c=1`, then `0 <= tt <= 255`, and the shift is performed by `tt+1` bits. If `s!=0` and `c=0`, then the shift amount is provided to the instruction as a top-of-stack _Integer_ in range `0...256`.
`1 <= d <= 3`  -  Indicates which results of division are required: `1` - only the quotient, `2` - only the remainder, `3` - both.
`0 <= f <= 2`  -  Rounding mode: `0` - floor, `1` - nearest integer, `2` - ceiling.
All instructions below are variants of this.

description: `q=floor(x/y)`, `r=x-y*q`

name: DIVR
description: `q’=round(x/y)`, `r’=x-y*q’`

name: MULDIV
description: `q=floor(x*y/z)`

name: MULDIVR
description: `q'=round(x*y/z)`

name: MULDIVMOD
description: `q=floor(x*y/z)`, `r=x*y-z*q`

description:
`0 <= y <= 1023`
